plate','artifact.php'),(3278,42,'_wp_trash_meta_status','publish'),(3279,42,'_wp_trash_meta_time','1362076177'),(3280,25,'_wp_trash_meta_status','publish'),(3281,25,'_wp_trash_meta_time','1362076379'),(3289,1017,'_wp_attached_file','2013/02/Anatomy-of-the-Ear.jpg'),(3290,1017,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:2484;s:6:\"height\";i:1479;s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"2013/02/Anatomy-of-the-Ear.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:3:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"Anatomy-of-the-Ear-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"Anatomy-of-the-Ear-300x178.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:178;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:5:\"large\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:31:\"Anatomy-of-the-Ear-1024x609.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:1024;s:6:\"height\";i:609;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3292,964,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt',''),(3352,967,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<h3 class=\"crimson\">How many decibels are too many?</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nAn increase in decibels is a multiple of how many times a sound is intensified. For example, if a noise increases by 10 on the decibel scale it has grown 10 times more powerful.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nYou are surrounded by sounds of varying decibels every day, most are well below the danger level, such as office conversation or white noise from a humming air conditioner (both are about 60 dB). But, noises that are 85 dB or higher put your hearing at risk. Examples of sounds that exceed this danger level include the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Motorcycles</li>\r\n<li>Gunfire</li>\r\n<li>Fireworks</li>\r\n<li>Subways</li>\r\n<li>Airplanes</li>\r\n<li>Jackhammers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\nThe general rule is that the louder the sound to which you are exposed, the less time it will take before hearing loss occurs. Follow this simple advice:</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><b><i>Avoid noises that are too loud, too close, or last too long.</i></b><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a></p></p>\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Does your job put you at high risk of hearing loss?</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nSome professions put you at greater risk of hearing loss than others, due to regular exposure to excessive noise. These include the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Public service (e.g., firefighting, ambulance driving)</li>\r\n<li>Industry and factory work</li>\r\n<li>Construction work</li>\r\n<li>Music and entertainment</li>\r\n<li>Military service</li>\r\n<li>Farming</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\nRecreational activities may also cost you your hearing if you do not take proper care to protect your ears. Examples of risky activities include the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hunting</li>\r\n<li>Attending concerts</li>\r\n<li>Going to dance clubs</li>\r\n<li>Blasting MP3 players while wearing ear buds</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Save your hearing—drop the decibels</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nUnlike other forms of hearing loss, NIHL can be prevented when you learn to recognize the risks and take reasonable precautions. If you are at high risk of exposure to 85 dB or greater, review our tips for avoiding hearing. If you are concerned damage has already been done, discuss your options for avoiding further damage with a hearing care professional.\r\n</p>\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" /></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]</a> National Institute on Deafness and Other Communication Disorders. <a href=\"http://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/hearing/pages/noise.aspx\">http://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/hearing/pages/noise.aspx</a>.</p>\r\n<p><br/></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(3403,969,'wpcf-fact2','The inner ear is no larger than a pencil eraser in circumference.'),(3404,969,'wpcf-fact3','Your sense of hearing is dependent upon tiny hairs deep inside your ear. If you lose these hairs, you lose your hearing.'),(3405,969,'wpcf-fact4','You do not need to clean wax out of your ears unless you have an abnormal condition. Ears clean themselves as needed by pushing excess wax out as needed.'),(3406,969,'wpcf-fact5','The majority of individuals suffering from hearing loss are under the age of 65.'),(3407,969,'wpcf-fact6','The number one cause of hearing loss is exposure to excessively loud sounds (85 decibels or higher).'),(3408,969,'wpcf-fact7','Your hearing can be damaged permanently even after a single incident of exposure to extremely loud noise (shotgun blast, explosion, etc.).'),(3409,969,'wpcf-fact8','Your ears never stop hearing, even when you sleep. Your brain just ignores incoming sounds.'),(3410,969,'wpcf-fact9','Your ears are more than just necessary for hearing; they also help you keep your balance.'),(3411,969,'wpcf-fact10','Not every living thing uses ears to hear. Snakes hear threw their jawbones, for example, while fish hear in response to pressure changes through ridges along their bodies and male mosquitoes hear through the thousands of miniscule hairs along their antennae.'),(3412,969,'wpcf-dwnld-pdf',''),(3413,969,'wpcf-takeaction-head',''),(3417,969,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<h3 class=\"crimson\">The following are ten fun facts about hearing:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The smallest bones in the human body are located in the middle ear: the <i>incus</i>, the <i>malleus</i>, and the <i>stapes</i> (also called the anvil, hammer, and stirrup) – collectively known as the <i>ossicles</i>.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>The inner ear is no larger than a pencil eraser in circumference.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>Your sense of hearing is dependent upon tiny hairs deep inside your ear. If you lose these hairs, you lose your hearing.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>You do not need to clean wax out of your ears unless you have an abnormal condition. Ears clean themselves as needed by pushing excess wax out as needed.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>The majority of individuals suffering from hearing loss are under the age of 65.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>The number one cause of hearing loss is exposure to excessively loud sounds (85 decibels or higher).</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>Your hearing can be damaged permanently even after a single incident of exposure to extremely loud noise (shotgun blast, explosion, etc.).</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>Your ears never stop hearing, even when you sleep. Your brain just ignores incoming sounds.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>Your ears are more than just necessary for hearing; they also help you keep your balance.</li>\r\n<br/>\r\n	<li>Not every living thing uses ears to hear. Snakes hear threw their jawbones, for example, while fish hear in response to pressure changes through ridges along their bodies and male mosquitoes hear through the thousands of miniscule hairs along their antennae.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\nIf you or a family member is struggling with hearing loss, help is available. Contact a hearing care professional today and preserve this life-enriching sense.'),(3429,971,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Do you frequently ask people to repeat themselves?</li>\r\n	<li>When in a group, do you find it difficult to keep up with the conversation?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you often complain about others mumbling or not speaking clearly?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you have difficulty understanding what someone else is saying when you are in a crowded place (restaurant, store, office, etc.)?</li>\r\n	<li>Are children or women with high voices particularly difficult to understand?</li>\r\n	<li>Do others complain that you have the volume of your TV or radio turned up way too high?</li>\r\n	<li>Are you sometimes embarrassed to find you’ve responded inappropriately to what someone else has said?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you hear a ringing in your ears when there is no apparent outside source?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you find it harder to understand people when you are not face-to-face with them?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you find yourself concentrating extra hard when talking to someone on the telephone?</li>\r\n	<li>At the end of the day, are you exhausted after having done nothing but talk or listen to others?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you find yourself avoiding going out with friends or attending family gatherings more than you used to?</li>\r\n	<li>Do/did your parents or other close relatives suffer from hearing loss?</li>\r\n	<li>Do/did you work in any environments that exposed you to very loud sounds either once or over a long period?</li>\r\n	<li>Do/did you engage in recreational activities that exposed you to very loud sounds either once or over a long period?</li>\r\n	<li>Do/did you take medications known to be potentially harmful to your hearing?</li>\r\n	<li>Have you been diagnosed with a heart or circulatory ailment, diabetes, or thyroid condition?</li>\r\n	<li>Have you ever been surprised to find a police car, fire engine, or ambulance had come up right behind you while driving before you heard their siren?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you find you are not being invited out as often by friends or over to family members’ homes?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you find people around you reacting to sounds (dog barking, children laughing, birds singing) that you just don’t hear?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>'),(3432,971,'wpcf-subpage-content',''),(3447,975,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt',''),(3449,975,'wpcf-subpage-content','<h3 class=\"crimson\">Injury of the outer ear</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nYour outer ear consists of the <i>pinna</i> or <i>auricle</i> (the visible part on the side of your head and the ear canal). The pinna catches sounds from the air and funnels it further into the ear. Any injury that damages your outer ear, such as a severe burn that requires amputation of the pinna, is likely to affect sound intake.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Blockage of the ear canal</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThe ear canal can become blocked due to intrusion by a foreign object (particles of food, toy parts, or insects) or from excess <i>cerumen</i> (earwax) buildup. Never try to remove anything lodged in your ear with a cotton swab or similar device! Seek help from a medical or hearing care professional to avoid further damage – especially puncturing your eardrum.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Infections of the outer or middle ear</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThese ear infections are particularly common in babies who nurse from bottles lying flat on their backs, allowing milk or formula to back up into the Eustachian tube, enter the middle ear, and cause infections. Ear infections are not just for kids – anyone can get an ear infection. Never ignore an ear infection. If not treated promptly, an ear infection can lead to permanent hearing loss or worse.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Perforation of the eardrum</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThe <i>tympanic membrane </i>(eardrum) is a major component of your hearing system, which vibrates in response to sounds conducted down the ear canal from the pinna. If it cannot vibrate, sound cannot travel properly into the middle ear. As mentioned above, keep foreign objects out of your ear canal, because the eardrum is not as deeply set in your ear canal as you may think. Trying to clean out earwax is an unfortunately common cause of conductive hearing loss – and one of the most easily avoided.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Congenital deformities</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nSome people are born with deformities (usually the result of genetics) that may cause malformation or absence of vital hearing systems, such as the ear canal or other structures.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nWhen it comes to sensorineural hearing loss, damage to the inner ear or along the auditory pathway from the inner ear prevents sound from reaching the brain. Again, there are many possible causes.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Birth injuries and hereditary conditions</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nPremature birth resulting in developmental issues or a complicated birth involving <i>atoxia</i> (lack of oxygen to the brain) may cause or contribute to hearing loss. Hereditary conditions, including genetic syndromes such as Down’s syndrome, Waardenburg syndrome, Treacher-Collins syndrome, and Neurofibromatosis (Type II), are linked to hearing loss and deafness.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Illnesses, injuries, and infections</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nEar infections can damage the workings of your inner ear just as they do the outer and middle. Diseases that affect multiple body systems, such as meningitis, rubella (German measles), and other viruses can wreak havoc on your hearing or, if you are pregnant when infected, your unborn baby’s developing ears. Hearing loss may also be symptomatic of a tumor. Another less common cause of hearing loss is injury, such as traumatic brain injury (TBI) and other head injuries.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Medications</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nSome prescription medications intended to fight illnesses can damage hearing. <i>Ototoxic </i>medications are toxic to the auditory system and can cause hearing loss, <i>tinnitus</i> (ringing in the ears), balance problems, and other disruptions that may be temporary or permanent. Some examples include chemotherapy drugs and salicylate pain relievers (aspirin).<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a>\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Presbycusis</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n<i>Presbycusis</i> (hearing loss associated with aging) is commonly associated causes of hearing loss — but interestingly, it’s not the most common. That honor goes to…\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Noise exposure</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nAll it takes is one extremely loud noise (100 decibels (dB) or more) or exposure over time to loud noises of more than 85 dB. It is the most common cause of hearing loss, causing vital hair cells to fall out and other damage that cannot be repaired. The best treatment is prevention.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Preventing hearing loss</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nTaking reasonable precautions to protect your child’s or your own hearing can help you avoid many causes of hearing impairment.  However, if you have already suffered enough damage to cause ringing in your ears or find it difficult to hear someone talking a few feet away, don’t hesitate to seek the advice of a hearing care professional on how to safeguard against losing more — or all — of your hearing.\r\n</p>\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" /></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a> American Speech-Language-Hearing Association. <a href=\"http://www.asha.org/public/hearing/Ototoxic-Medications/\">http://www.asha.org/public/hearing/Ototoxic-Medications/</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(3450,1084,'_edit_last','1'),(3451,1084,'_edit_lock','1362684444:1'),(3455,1084,'_wp_page_template','artifact.php'),(3457,1084,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt',''),(3459,976,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<h3 class=\"crimson\">Tinnitus</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nTinnitus is a perception of sounds for which there is no external source. Many people describe tinnitus as ringing, while others experience it as humming, buzzing, or whistling. Tinnitus is a <i>symptom</i> of hearing impairment, not a cause, as many people mistakenly believe. The most common cause of tinnitus is noise exposure. While there is currently no cure for this condition, the use of hearing aids with tinnitus suppression features such as white noise generation have been found to provide wearers with significant relief from the irritating sounds.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Vertigo</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nVertigo refers to an unexplained perception that the world is spinning or whirling around you. Disorienting and nauseating, it is often accompanied by balance issues that can be particularly dangerous to older people, putting them at greater risk of falls and injuries. Some vertigo is temporary and connected to a specific illness, while others experience chronic vertigo, which flares up periodically and for which doctors may not be able to pinpoint a cause. Like tinnitus, vertigo is a symptom, not a syndrome itself. If you experience vertigo in conjunction with hearing loss, you should seek medical attention, as the cause may be a benign growth on the inner ear or an infection of the ear. Prompt treatment of either could save your hearing.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Meniere’s disease</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThis inner ear disorder has been linked to episodes of vertigo, hearing loss, imbalance, tinnitus, and other disturbances. The cause remains unknown. While there are some medications available to treat the symptoms, no cure currently exists for the condition itself. An estimated 615,000 people suffer from Meniere’s disease in the US alone<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a>.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Waardenburg syndrome</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nWaardenburg syndrome actually covers a group of inherited conditions and appears as one of four main types. Deafness is more common in the Type II version. The syndrome affects the distribution of pigment through the body, which can produce unusual eye color, skin tone, and/or hair color, as well as affect hearing. Only one parent has to be a carrier of this genetic defect for it to pass down to a child, so it is important if the syndrome is in your family that you are tested for the gene before having children. There is no treatment for the condition itself, only the various symptoms. Depending on the severity of hearing loss, hearing aids or a cochlear implant may help.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Diabetes</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nPeople with diabetes are two times more likely to suffer hearing loss than those without the condition<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn2\"><sup>[2]</sup></a>. Diabetes refers to a group of diseases associated with high blood glucose levels caused by an inability to produce or use insulin properly. Nearly 26 million US citizens have a form of diabetes, yet most don’t realize that hearing loss is yet another risk of the disease, due to high blood sugar damaging the tiny blood vessels and nerves in the inner ear. Dietary changes or insulin injections are the usual treatments. Your physician can refer you to a hearing care professional for help finding the right hearing aids to improve any hearing loss.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Meningitis</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nMeningitis is a very serious illness that often starts out mimicking the symptoms of a cold or the flu, but then progressively worsens. It is caused by an infection that inflames the membranes of the spinal cord. The source may be bacterial, viral, or fungal in nature. Left untreated, meningitis has the potential to lead to serious complications such as hearing loss and death. Hearing loss in children often results from bacterial infections, including certain forms of meningitis. In some cases, the hearing loss may not develop right away, but rather show up months after recovery from meningitis. If your child contracts meningitis, make sure you pay particular attention for signs of hearing loss and have your family doctor screen his or her hearing. Prompt response and treatment can sometimes avert permanent deafness.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Measels, Mumps, Rubella, and Chickenpox</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThese viruses are all associated with sudden hearing loss. Once commonly acquired during childhood, vaccinations now offer protection. Measles are a very contagious virus that can lead to death if left untreated. Deafness may result if the Eustachian tube becomes blocked, causing a collapse of the walls in the middle ear that cuts off airflow from the throat.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nRubella can affect a child <i>in utero</i> if his or her mother contracts the virus while pregnant, causing blindness and/or hearing loss.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nMumps affects a set of salivary glands and can lead to serious complications, including encephalitis and hearing loss.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nChickenpox is very contagious and once was an expected, if dreaded, childhood event. Thanks to the chickenpox vaccine, children no longer have to suffer through weeks of itchy bumps. Even more importantly, adult women who never had chickenpox can avoid contracting it during pregnancy, protecting their baby from birth defects that include deafness.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nOther serious conditions, including heart disease and dementia, have been linked to hearing loss. For more information about these and related illnesses, speak to your personal physician or a hearing care professional.\r\n</p>\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" /></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a> The National Institute on Deafness and Other Communication Disorders (NIDCD). <a href=\"http://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/balance/pages/meniere.aspx\">http://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/balance/pages/meniere.aspx</a>.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref2\"><sup>[2]</sup></a> National Institutes of Health. <i>NIH News.</i> <a href=\"http://www.nih.gov/news/health/jun2008/niddk-16.htm\">http://www.nih.gov/news/health/jun2008/niddk-16.htm</a>.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(3469,160,'wpcf-subpage-content','To promote better understanding of what the people in your life who have hearing loss are experiencing, here are ten things you should know about hearing loss:\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Hearing loss is called, “the invisible handicap” because there are no outward signs of difficulty or disorder, and the loss is usually gradual (over a period of years) and painless.\r\n	<li>Among seniors, hearing loss is the most prevalent medical condition, following arthritis and hypertension.\r\n	<li>People with diabetes are twice as likely to have hearing loss as those who do not have diabetes.\r\n	<li>Smokers and overweight individuals are also at increased risk of hearing loss.\r\n	<li>Inability to hear and understand instructions by physicians, pharmacists, or caregivers can put personal health in jeopardy.\r\n	<li>Men that regularly use aspirin, acetaminophen, and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs experience more hearing loss.\r\n	<li>In addition, men that take <i>phosphodiesterase</i> (PDE) inhibitors are twice as likely to develop hearing loss as men who do not.\r\n	<li>Depression, isolation, and alienation can plague those who have hearing loss.\r\n	<li>Noise-induced hearing loss is the most common cause of hearing loss in adults and children, versus hearing loss caused by the aging process or birth defects.\r\n	<li>Noise-induced hearing loss is a function of volume and duration. Government research suggests that the safe decibel (dB) exposure limit before hearing loss results is a maximum of 85dB, which is the equivalent of listening to busy city traffic, for eight hours a day.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\nFor more information on possible causes and solutions for hearing loss, contact your personal physician or a hearing care professional. They can help you make good decisions in order to preserve your hearing, test you for any hearing loss, or provide guidance on what to do next if you already know you aren’t hearing things as well as you used to.'),(3473,10,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<h3 class=\"crimson\">Different kinds of tinnitus</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nThe five manifestations of tinnitus are as follows:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Objective.</b> Can also be heard by a doctor, occurs rarely, and is usually due to tension or vascular deformities. This variant usually disappears after treatment of a specific cause.</li>\r\n<li><b>Subjective.</b> The most common type of tinnitus, when only you can hear the noise. It appears suddenly and lasts up to three months (acute) or ends in 12 months (subacute).</li>\r\n<li><b>Chronic.</b> Typically lasts longer than 12 months and may be permanent.</li>\r\n<li><b>Compensated.</b> You may manage well despite the tinnitus, learning to ignore or get used to the ringing over time so that your quality of life isn’t impacted by the condition.</li>\r\n<li><b>Chronically complex (or uncompensated).</b> You are almost constantly aware of the noise in your ears, so much so that your quality of life is severely compromised.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Tinnitus relief</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nWhile there is no cure for tinnitus yet, options are available that address the irritation it causes. Noise generators or maskers provide distractions for your hearing system, so that it concentrates on these more soothing external sounds. So-called “white noise,” like the hum of a fan and “pink noise,” such as a simulated heartbeat have been found to provide significant relief.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nSince complete masking of tinnitus would require at least the same volume as the tinnitus sound, they could become just as uncomfortable. However, noise generators producing comforting sounds are nearly as effective at countering the ringing. Your brain learns to concentrate on these softer external sounds, rather than fixating on the internal noise.\r\n</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Tinnitus and hearing loss</h3>\r\n<p>\r\nMore than 50 percent of those suffering from tinnitus also have an inner ear hearing impairment. One example is <i>hyperacusis, </i>or a perception that certain environmental sounds are painfully loud when no one else with normal hearing does.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nBecause of the association between tinnitus and hearing loss, treatment with hearing aids is often recommended. Hearing aids improve your ability to hear the external world, which in turn reduces the distraction of internal noise. Some hearing aids also treat hyperacusis by balancing out your volume perception, providing additional relief.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nHearing aids with tinnitus therapy features include their own sound generators to counteract the ringing with white or pink noise, or a combination of masking sounds. Your hearing care professional can help you determine the type of hearing aids and tinnitus therapy that appropriate for your tinnitus.\r\n</p>\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" /></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a> American Tinnitus Association. <a href=\"http://www.ata.org/\">http://www.ata.org/</a>.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(3490,1123,'_wp_attached_file','2013/02/pdf_print_255x30.png'),(3491,1123,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:255;s:6:\"height\";i:30;s:4:\"file\";s:28:\"2013/02/pdf_print_255x30.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"pdf_print_255x30-150x30.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:30;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3492,1124,'_wp_attached_file','2013/02/20130117_SIE12-302_mockup-comps.png'),(3493,1124,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:21;s:6:\"height\";i:21;s:4:\"file\";s:43:\"2013/02/20130117_SIE12-302_mockup-comps.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:0:{}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3502,1134,'_wp_attached_file','2013/02/20130117_SIE12-302_mockup-comps.png'),(3503,1134,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:21;s:6:\"height\";i:21;s:4:\"file\";s:43:\"2013/02/20130117_SIE12-302_mockup-comps.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:0:{}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";i:0;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:0;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";i:0;s:3:\"iso\";i:0;s:13:\"shutter_speed\";i:0;s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3508,160,'wpcf-fact2','Among seniors, hearing loss is the most prevalent medical condition, following arthritis and hypertension.'),(3509,160,'wpcf-fact3','People with diabetes are twice as likely to have hearing loss as those who do not have diabetes.'),(3510,160,'wpcf-fact4','Smokers and overweight individuals are also at increased risk of hearing loss.'),(3511,160,'wpcf-fact5','Inability to hear and understand instructions by physicians, pharmacists, or caregivers can put personal health in jeopardy.'),(3512,160,'wpcf-fact6','Men that regularly use aspirin, acetaminophen, and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs experience more hearing loss.'),(3513,160,'wpcf-fact7','In addition, men that take phosphodiesterase (PDE) inhibitors are twice as likely to develop hearing loss as men who do not.'),(3514,160,'wpcf-fact8','Depression, isolation, and alienation can plague those who have hearing loss.'),(3515,160,'wpcf-fact10','Noise-induced hearing loss is a function of volume and duration. Government research suggests that the safe decibel (dB) exposure limit before hearing loss results is a maximum of 85dB, which is the equivalent of listening to busy city traffic, for eight hours a day.'),(3516,160,'wpcf-dwnld-pdf',''),(3527,160,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt',''),(3563,579,'wpcf-fact2','How often should I clean my hearing aids?'),(3564,579,'wpcf-fact3','Should I wear my new hearing aids all the time right from the start or follow a specific schedule to get used to them?'),(3565,579,'wpcf-fact4','What happens if I don’t like the way my hearing aids sound?'),(3566,579,'wpcf-fact5','My new hearing aids have so many gadgets on them—can you show me how to work each one?'),(3567,579,'wpcf-fact6','(For hearing aids without rechargeable batteries) How do I know it’s time to change my battery and how do I do so?'),(3568,579,'wpcf-fact7','Do I need to schedule a follow up appointment today?'),(3569,579,'wpcf-fact8','(For non-waterproof hearing aids) What should I do if my hearing aids accidentally get wet?'),(3570,579,'wpcf-fact9','What kind of routine service and repair will my hearing aids need? Is it all covered by the warranty?'),(3571,579,'wpcf-fact10','What happens if I’m unhappy with my hearing aids?'),(3572,579,'wpcf-dwnld-pdf',''),(3573,579,'wpcf-takeaction-head',''),(3580,497,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt','<p>The truth is hearing loss affects people of all ages and is more often the result of conditions wholly unrelated to getting older. Unfortunately, the perception remains, and so those who could recover use of this sense fail to take the necessary steps. The result is a life of increasing isolation, loss of experiences and relationships that takes a profound emotional toll.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Emotional fallout of hearing loss</h3>\r\n<p><i>“I find myself losing my temper with my grandchildren because they mumble all the time.”</i></p>\r\n<p><i>“Everyone cracked up when the boss asked me about last month’s numbers, and I thought she said something about the sand in summer. I don’t speak up in meetings anymore.”</i></p>\r\n<p><i>“I stopped going to my weekly mah-jongg game because I’m tired of asking everyone to repeat themselves—and I can tell they’re sick of it, too.”</i></p>\r\n<p>Do any of these sound familiar? Even if you haven’t experienced these exact scenarios, the emotions they evoke probably still resonate. The National Council on Aging<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a> studied the consequences of untreated hearing loss and found sufferers experience the following common feelings:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sadness</li>\r\n<li>Frustration</li>\r\n<li>Embarrassment</li>\r\n<li>Anxiety</li>\r\n<li>Paranoia</li>\r\n<li>Insecurity</li>\r\n<li>Anger</li>\r\n<li>Loss of self-confidence</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Loss of hearing interferes with your ability to enjoy recreation, vacation, hobbies, and other pastimes and takes you out of the social scene. The resulting loneliness and depression robs you of precious years. Isn’t this a far worse outcome than wearing hearing instruments that you fear may make you look old?</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"crimson\">Wearing hearing aids is no longer a stigma</h3>\r\n<p>You may still believe the stubborn myth that wearing hearing instruments carries a social stigma. Perhaps this was true many years ago, when hearing aids were large, unsightly, and only worn by the elderly. However, today’s hearing aids are very different creations, made to suit the needs of Baby Boomers and younger generations who are affected more than ever by hearing loss. Many hearing aids rest wholly inside the ear canal or are tucked securely behind the ear, with clear tubes fitted in the ear that are virtually invisible. Others are made to be seen, coming in sleek styles and colors, much like fancy ear buds for MP3 players.</p>\r\n<p>Think about it like this—glasses also used to be considered stigmatizing devices, with thick lenses and clunky frames. Yet when was the last time you heard someone wearing glasses called “four eyes” or otherwise teased? Glasses now come in so many different styles, shapes, and colors that they are considered fashion accessories—some people wear them who don’t even need vision correction!</p>\r\n<p>The same can be said for hearing aids. They have become marvels of modern technology—small, powerful, and as visible or unnoticeable as you prefer. Given the choice between losing out on the pleasures of life—fun, career success, companionship, family—and wearing what is fast becoming a cutting edge accessory, not taking steps to decrease or end your hearing loss just doesn’t make sense.</p>\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" /></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div class=\"footnote\">\r\n<p><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftnref1\"><sup>[1]</sup></a> National Council on Aging. <a href=\"http://www.ncoa.org/assets/files/pdf/center-for-healthy-aging/NCOA-Study-1999.pdf\">http://www.ncoa.org/assets/files/pdf/center-for-healthy-aging/NCOA-Study-1999.pdf</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(3581,711,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3584,711,'wpcf-types-main-cntnt',''),(3585,633,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3588,583,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3592,31,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3594,648,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3597,642,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3599,966,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3601,966,'wpcf-take-action-head','Take Action'),(3602,966,'wpcf-quiz-cta1-copy','DOWNLOAD OUR <br/>HEARING AID GUIDE'),(3603,966,'wpcf-quiz-cta1-link','#cta1'),(3604,966,'wpcf-quiz-cta2-copy','CONTACT A HEARING <br/>CARE PROVIDER'),(3605,966,'wpcf-quiz-cta2-link','#cta2'),(3606,966,'wpcf-quiz-herotext','This ten-question quiz will test your knowledge on the science of hearing. Click the answer you think is correct, then click “Submit”. If you’re right, click “Next” to move on to the following question. Good luck.'),(3607,966,'wpcf-quiz-related-articles-head','Related Links'),(3608,966,'wpcf-quiz-link1','1. Nam libero tempore, culim soluta'),(3609,966,'wpcf-quiz-link1-url','#1'),(3610,966,'wpcf-quiz-link2','2. Temporibus autem quibusdam et aut officiis'),(3611,966,'wpcf-quiz-link2-url','#2'),(3612,966,'wpcf-quiz-link3','3. architecto beatae vitae dicta sunt explicabo'),(3613,966,'wpcf-quiz-link3-url','#3'),(3614,966,'wpcf-quiz-link4','4. architecto beatae vitae dicta sunt explicabo'),(3615,966,'wpcf-quiz-link4-url','#4'),(3616,975,'_su_title','Causes of Hearing Loss | Hearingaids.com'),(3617,975,'_su_description','Hearingaids.com presents the typical causes of hearing loss and offers advice on prevention.'),(3618,975,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3620,179,'_su_title','Interactive Hearing Test | Hearingaids.com'),(3621,179,'_su_description','Hearingaids.com provides a hearing screening test online.'),(3622,179,'_su_rich_snippet_type','none'),(3624,976,'_su_title','Related Medical Condit