oved the travel experience for numerous hearing impaired tourists. Instead of straining to hear tour guides, missing boarding announcements, and struggling to negotiate unfamiliar public transportation, hearing aid wearers can enjoy trips without extra hassle and worry. But, it’s important to protect and maintain your hearing aids while traveling, so that they continue to provide the top performance you need while away from home.','Traveling with Hearing Aids','','inherit','closed','closed','','648-revision-6','','','2013-02-28 10:27:56','2013-02-28 18:27:56','',648,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/648-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(1176,3,'2013-03-04 13:22:14','2013-03-04 21:22:14','Hearing aids have improved the travel experience for numerous hearing impaired tourists. Instead of straining to hear tour guides, missing boarding announcements, and struggling to negotiate unfamiliar public transportation, hearing aid wearers can enjoy trips without extra hassle and worry. But, it’s important to protect and maintain your hearing aids while traveling, so that they continue to provide the top performance you need while away from home.','Traveling with Hearing Aids','','inherit','closed','closed','','648-revision-7','','','2013-03-04 13:22:14','2013-03-04 21:22:14','',648,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/648-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(1177,3,'2013-02-28 10:28:39','2013-02-28 18:28:39','Most digital hearing aids are equipped with options to allow you to hear in a variety of environments. As you change settings throughout the day, you can push a button on your hearing aids to select a program appropriate to your surroundings. Or, if you have more advanced digital hearing aids, they will switch programs automatically based on an analysis of environmental sounds. Your audiologist or other hearing care professional will set up the programs at your fitting and tweak them as necessary during follow-up visits.','Settings for Different Environments','','inherit','closed','closed','','642-revision-6','','','2013-02-28 10:28:39','2013-02-28 18:28:39','',642,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/642-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(1178,3,'2013-02-28 10:03:50','2013-02-28 18:03:50','','How Do We Hear Quiz','','inherit','closed','closed','','966-revision','','','2013-02-28 10:03:50','2013-02-28 18:03:50','',966,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/966-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1179,9,'2013-02-28 17:47:13','2013-03-01 01:47:13','If you already read our types of hearing loss overview, you know that there are several types of hearing loss. There are also many causes.','Causes of Hearing Loss','','inherit','closed','closed','','975-revision-6','','','2013-02-28 17:47:13','2013-03-01 01:47:13','',975,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/975-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(1180,9,'2013-02-28 10:02:11','2013-02-28 18:02:11','[slickquiz id=1]\r\n\r\n','Interactive Hearing Test','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-26','','','2013-02-28 10:02:11','2013-02-28 18:02:11','',179,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/179-revision-26/',0,'revision','',0),(1181,9,'2013-02-28 18:12:05','2013-03-01 02:12:05','Hearing loss is often a symptom or outcome of other medical conditions, which can be very serious or even life threatening. This is yet another reason that it is so important to recognize the signs of hearing loss and seek treatment from a hearing care professional as soon as possible. More than your hearing may be at stake.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nThe following are a sampling of other illnesses and afflictions linked to hearing loss. A qualified otolaryngologist (ear, nose, and throat doctor or ENT) or certified audiologist can help diagnose these conditions and provide recommendations for treatment.','Related Medical Conditions','','inherit','closed','closed','','976-revision-8','','','2013-02-28 18:12:05','2013-03-01 02:12:05','',976,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/976-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(1182,9,'2013-03-04 11:12:21','2013-03-04 19:12:21','Do you find yourself asking others to repeat themselves frequently during conversation? Are you straining to understand what the person across the table from you is saying in a crowded restaurant?\r\n\r\n</br></br>\r\n\r\nThese are just two of the indicators that you may have hearing loss. The following checklist can help you figure out if you might benefit from seeing a hearing care professional. If you answer “yes” to one or more of these, you should schedule an appointment as soon as possible. The sooner you seek treatment for hearing loss, the more of your remaining hearing can be protected.','Signs & Symptoms Checklist','','inherit','closed','closed','','971-revision-20','','','2013-03-04 11:12:21','2013-03-04 19:12:21','',971,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/971-revision-20/',0,'revision','',0),(1183,9,'2013-02-28 18:35:11','2013-03-01 02:35:11','When you see a hearing care professional for diagnosis of your hearing loss, he or she is likely to tell you more than simply, “You have lost some hearing.” Rather, you will probably be told that you have a specific type of hearing loss:\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>conductive</li>\r\n	<li>sensorineural</li>\r\n	<li>mixed</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br/>\r\nHere’s a brief overview of each hearing loss type, its likely causes, and the treatment options usually proposed.','Types of Hearing Loss','','inherit','closed','closed','','210-revision-24','','','2013-02-28 18:35:11','2013-03-01 02:35:11','',210,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/210-revision-24/',0,'revision','',0),(1184,9,'2013-03-04 10:54:18','2013-03-04 18:54:18','To understand hearing loss, it helps to know the basic mechanics of how we hear. Our ears, when working properly, are sophisticated organs capable of processing sounds from the scarcely audible to extremely loud. Our ears can assess volume and how close or far away sounds are and identify where sounds originate with a great deal of accuracy. The following explains how this deceptively simple process works.','How We Hear','','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-19','','','2013-03-04 10:54:18','2013-03-04 18:54:18','',6,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/6-revision-19/',0,'revision','',0),(1185,9,'2013-03-01 15:21:08','2013-03-01 23:21:08','How you hear naturally is fascinating. Think about it.  All of the components of this intricately designed process must work at peak function to carry waves in the air around you to your brain, where they are understood as distinct sounds. Hearing allows you to communicate, learn, experience, and enjoy the world around you.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nText for box above facts: The following are ten fun facts about hearing:\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nText for box below facts: If you or a family member is struggling with hearing loss, help is available. Contact a hearing care professional today and preserve this life-enriching sense.','10 Cool Facts about Hearing','','inherit','closed','closed','','969-revision-13','','','2013-03-01 15:21:08','2013-03-01 23:21:08','',969,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/969-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(1186,9,'2013-02-28 13:20:11','2013-02-28 21:20:11','<a href=\"http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Anatomy-of-the-Ear.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-1017\" alt=\"Anatomy of the Ear\" src=\"http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Anatomy-of-the-Ear.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"296\" /></a>','Anatomy of the Ear','','inherit','closed','closed','','964-revision-5','','','2013-02-28 13:20:11','2013-02-28 21:20:11','',964,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/964-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(1187,9,'2013-02-28 16:28:05','2013-03-01 00:28:05','Your ears can be damaged if you are overexposed to excessive noise—either one-time exposure to an extremely loud sound (e.g., an explosion) or regular exposure over time (e.g., heavy machinery on the job). This is called <i>noise-induced hearing loss</i> (NIHL). Once you lose vital structures like the hair cells that send sound impulses to your brain, they cannot be repaired. So, how do you know what is just loud versus sound levels that are dangerous to your hearing?\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nThe loudness of sound is measurable, using units called <i>decibels</i> (dB). A decibel unit expresses the relative intensity of sounds on a scale from zero (think a gentle breeze) to about 120 dB (think fireworks). Normal speech is typically between 50 to 60 dB.','What are Decibels?','','inherit','closed','closed','','967-revision-15','','','2013-02-28 16:28:05','2013-03-01 00:28:05','',967,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/967-revision-15/',0,'revision','',0),(1188,3,'2013-03-04 13:45:34','2013-03-04 21:45:34','[slickquiz id=2]','How Do We Hear Quiz','','inherit','closed','closed','','966-revision-2','','','2013-03-04 13:45:34','2013-03-04 21:45:34','',966,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/966-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(1189,9,'2013-03-04 14:21:40','2013-03-04 22:21:40','[slickquiz id=2]','How Do We Hear Quiz','','inherit','closed','closed','','966-revision-3','','','2013-03-04 14:21:40','2013-03-04 22:21:40','',966,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/966-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1190,9,'2013-02-28 19:10:58','2013-03-01 03:10:58','Tinnitus affects up to 50 million people in the United States<a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a>. It is the number one disability suffered by combat veterans and affects at least one in every 10 American adults. Yet very few people, even those who have it, know what it is or what they can do to combat it.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nTinnitus comes from the Latin word <i>tinnire</i> (to ring) and is a perception of sound for which there is no actual external source. You may describe it as ringing in your ears, while to others it sounds like humming, buzzing, or whistling. Tinnitus is a symptom of some kind of damage to your auditory processing system, but is not itself a cause. The most common culprit is the same as for hearing loss — noise exposure. However, sometimes no specific cause can be identified.\r\n<div><br clear=\"all\" />\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>','Tinnitus','','inherit','closed','closed','','10-revision-11','','','2013-02-28 19:10:58','2013-03-01 03:10:58','',10,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/10-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(1191,1,'2013-03-01 15:24:15','2013-03-01 23:24:15','Researchers continue to learn more about hearing loss, its causes and contributing factors, and effects. There are ways to reduce the likelihood of losing your hearing in some cases, while others are simply beyond our control.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nText for above facts: To promote better understanding of what the people in your life who have hearing loss are experiencing, here are ten things you should know about hearing loss:\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nText for below facts: For more information on possible causes and solutions for hearing loss, contact your personal physician or a hearing care professional. They can help you make good decisions in order to preserve your hearing, test you for any hearing loss, or provide guidance on what to do next if you already know you aren’t hearing things as well as you used to. ','10 Things to Know about Hearing Loss','','inherit','closed','closed','','160-revision-25','','','2013-03-01 15:24:15','2013-03-01 23:24:15','',160,'http://10.2.10.246/ha.com/160-revision-25/',0,'revision','',0),(1192,3,'2013-03-04 14:20:24','2013-03-04 22:20:24','Your ears can be damaged if you are overexposed to excessive noise—either one-time exposure to an extremely loud sound (e.g., an explosion) or regular exposure over time (e.g., heavy machinery on the job). This is called <i>noise-induced hearing loss</i> (NIHL). Once you lose vital structures like the hair cells that send sound impulses to your brain, they cannot be repaired. So, how do you know what is just loud versus sound levels that are dangerous to your hearing?\r\n\r\nThe loudness of sound is measurable, using units called <i>decibels</i> (dB). A decibel unit expresses the relative intensity of sounds on 